    The Red House was a lovely experience and atmosphere. Beautiful building with the most stunning mosaic architecture, live music, attentive staff and wonderful food. The menu wasn’t big so you were not overwhelmed with choice. Traditional …
    The Red House was a lovely experience and atmosphere. Beautiful building with the most stunning mosaic architecture, live music, attentive staff and wonderful food. The menu wasn’t big so you were not overwhelmed with choice. Traditional Moroccan or french cuisine. I went with the prawn bisque, chicken and candied lemon tagine and the rice and almond rolls. The soup was a large portion so if not a big eater, I’d skip or try something else. The main was delicious, but be cautious, it’s piping hot. The desert was delicate, flavoursome and very enjoyable. Price wise, the food is reasonable as are the soft drinks. Wine is on the expensive side but to be expected in such culture. A must visit !!

    Excellent food in generous portions, from both the Moroccan and international menus. Service generally very good indeed and the dining room is beautifully decorated. The restaurant sort-of spoiled us for anything else in the area really, the other places we ate at when we ventured out were very disappointing in comparison.
    Onto the hotel side: The bedrooms are also very nice with good size beds and bathrooms, and the spa treatments are great too, even adapted the hammam to be suitable for pregnant ladies! The pool was a little chilly for us in early March, though there were a couple of sun worshippers who used it to cool down in between their baking sessions and it suited them perfectly for that. Breakfast was lovely every day, with a pre-order each night beforehand. We took ours mostly in the beautiful garden, beside the pool, opting for the restaurant on a couple of occasions when we were up before the sun had chance to warm things up. If you have a room larger than a Princess Double you could have taken breakfast in your room, we just didn't have a suitable table really.
    Can't leave a review without mentioning Abdel, who was the epitome of the Moroccan welcome. Nothing was too much trouble and he gave us an excellent briefing on the city the afternoon we arrived, as well as organising trips for us.
    Would definitely stay again and recommend it to anyone wanting to visit Marrakech.

    Hivernage

    Refined, modern Hivernage is known for nightlife, with a casino, cocktail lounges, hotel dance clubs and chic global restaurants with live music. The Royal Theatre, with domes and Ancient Egyptian–style columns, stages concerts in an amphitheater. Nearby, the Menara Gardens, with a huge reflecting pool and mountains in the background, date to the 12th century, and El-Harti Park has fountains and a rose garden.
